    <section class="methodology-section card">
      <h2>Ranking Methodology</h2>
      <p>Our analysis for the best high growth stocks for 2025 evaluates companies across several critical dimensions to ensure a comprehensive assessment:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Financial Health:</strong> We look for robust balance sheets, manageable debt-to-equity ratios, and strong cash flow generation capabilities.</li>
        <li><strong>Growth Trajectory:</strong> Historical and projected revenue and earnings growth are heavily weighted, prioritizing sustainable expansion over short-term spikes.</li>
        <li><strong>Valuation Metrics:</strong> P/E ratios, Price-to-Sales, and PEG ratios are compared against sector averages and historical norms to identify attractive entry points.</li>
        <li><strong>Competitive Moat:</strong> Companies with distinct competitive advantages, such as technological leadership, network effects, or strong brand equity, score higher.</li>
        <li><strong>Macroeconomic Resilience:</strong> The ability to perform well across different interest rate environments and economic cycles is considered crucial for long-term viability.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What defines a high growth stock in 2025?</summary>
        <p>A high growth stock typically demonstrates revenue growth exceeding 20% annually, operates in a rapidly expanding total addressable market (TAM), and is capturing significant market share from legacy incumbents.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Are high growth stocks riskier?</summary>
        <p>Yes, they generally carry higher volatility and risk. Their valuations are often based on future earnings expectations, making them sensitive to interest rate changes and any signs of slowing growth momentum.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How do interest rates affect growth stocks?</summary>
        <p>Higher interest rates typically compress the valuation multiples of growth stocks because future cash flows are discounted at a higher rate. Conversely, falling rates can act as a significant tailwind for growth equities.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Should I look at profitability or revenue for growth stocks?</summary>
        <p>While revenue growth is the primary driver, the market in 2025 heavily rewards companies that demonstrate a clear path to profitability or expanding free cash flow margins alongside their top-line expansion.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How many growth stocks should be in a balanced portfolio?</summary>
        <p>This depends on individual risk tolerance, but typically 10-20% of an equity portfolio allocated to hyper-growth names can provide significant upside while mitigating extreme portfolio volatility.</p>
      </details>

    </section>
